{"award_age":64.0,"bio_image":"full\/9f92dbb0374f24245c81083b971ce09b6941544d.jpg","category":"Physics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1908-05-23T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1991-01-30T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/4\/4a\/Bardeen.jpg\/220px-Bardeen.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Bardeen","mini_bio":"<p><b>John Bardeen<\/b> (May 23, 1908 \u2013 January 30, 1991) was an American <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Physicist\" title=\"Physicist\">physicist<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Electrical_engineer\" title=\"Electrical engineer\" class=\"mw-redirect\">electrical engineer<\/a>, the only person to have won the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> twice: first in 1956 with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/William_Shockley\" title=\"William Shockley\">William Shockley<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Walter_Houser_Brattain\" title=\"Walter Houser Brattain\">Walter Brattain<\/a> for the invention of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Transistor\" title=\"Transistor\">transistor<\/a>; and again in 1972 with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Leon_Cooper\" title=\"Leon Cooper\">Leon N Cooper<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Robert_Schrieffer\" title=\"John Robert Schrieffer\">John Robert Schrieffer<\/a> for a fundamental theory of conventional <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Superconductivity\" title=\"Superconductivity\">superconductivity<\/a> known as the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/BCS_theory\" title=\"BCS theory\">BCS theory<\/a>.<\/p><p>The transistor revolutionized the electronics industry, allowing the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Information_Age\" title=\"Information Age\">Information Age<\/a> to occur, and made possible the development of almost every modern electronic device, from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Telephone\" title=\"Telephone\">telephones<\/a> to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Computer\" title=\"Computer\">computers<\/a> to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Missile\" title=\"Missile\">missiles<\/a>. Bardeen's developments in superconductivity, which won him his second Nobel, are used in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nuclear_Magnetic_Resonance\" title=\"Nuclear Magnetic Resonance\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nuclear Magnetic Resonance<\/a> Spectroscopy (NMR) or its medical sub-tool <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Magnetic_resonance_imaging\" title=\"Magnetic resonance imaging\">magnetic resonance imaging<\/a> (MRI).<\/p><p>In 1990, John Bardeen appeared on <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Life_(magazine)\" title=\"Life (magazine)\">LIFE Magazine<\/a>'<\/i>s list of \"100 Most Influential Americans of the Century.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-washpost_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Bardeen#cite_note-washpost-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"John Bardeen","place_of_birth":"Madison, Wisconsin , U.S.","place_of_death":"Boston, Massachusetts , U.S.","text":"John Bardeen , Physics, 1972","year":1972.0}